-- U.S.-based taxable bond funds attract $4.5 bln - Lipper
-- By Sam Forgione
-- Thu Mar 20, 2014 05:08PM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, March 20 (Reuters) - Investors in U.S.-based funds poured $4.5 billion into taxable bond funds in the week ended March 19, marking the biggest inflows into the funds in five weeks, data from Thomson Reuters' Lipper service showed on Thursday.

Funds that mainly hold U.S. Treasuries attracted about $188 million in new cash, marking their first inflows in five weeks. Low-risk money market funds, meanwhile, posted $25.3 billion in outflows, marking their biggest withdrawals in four weeks.  Stock funds attracted $4.6 billion in new cash, marking their sixth straight week of inflows. Emerging market stock funds posted $1.1 billion in outflows, however, marking their biggest withdrawals in six weeks.  Funds that specialize in Chinese stocks posted $458 million in outflows, marking their biggest outflows since last June.